Here's a breakdown of your <code>calculateTotal</code> function:<br><br><pre><code>function calculateTotal(items) {
  return items.reduce((sum, item) => {
    return sum + (item.price * item.quantity);
  }, 0);
}</code></pre><br><strong>Line by line:</strong><br>1. Takes an array of <code>items</code> as input<br>2. Uses <code>.reduce()</code> to iterate through each item<br>3. Multiplies each item's <code>price</code> by its <code>quantity</code><br>4. Accumulates the running total starting from <code>0</code><br>5. Returns the final sum<br><br>This is a clean, functional approach. The accumulator pattern is idiomatic JavaScript. ✅

I found a couple of potential issues. Here's the improved version:<br><br><pre><code>function calculateTotal(items) {
  if (!Array.isArray(items) || items.length === 0) {
    return 0;
  }
  return items.reduce((sum, item) => {
    const price = Number(item.price) || 0;
    const quantity = Number(item.quantity) || 0;
    return sum + (price * quantity);
  }, 0);
}</code></pre><br><strong>Changes made:</strong><br>• Added guard clause for non-array or empty input<br>• Added <code>Number()</code> coercion with <code>|| 0</code> fallback for missing/invalid values<br>• Now handles <code>undefined</code>, <code>null</code>, and string values gracefully

Here are unit tests for <code>calculateTotal</code>:<br><br><pre><code>import { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';

describe('calculateTotal', () => {
  it('calculates total for multiple items', () => {
    const items = [
      { price: 10, quantity: 2 },
      { price: 5, quantity: 3 }
    ];
    expect(calculateTotal(items)).toBe(35);
  });

  it('returns 0 for an empty array', () => {
    expect(calculateTotal([])).toBe(0);
  });

  it('returns 0 for non-array input', () => {
    expect(calculateTotal(null)).toBe(0);
    expect(calculateTotal(undefined)).toBe(0);
  });

  it('handles missing price gracefully', () => {
    const items = [{ quantity: 2 }];
    expect(calculateTotal(items)).toBe(0);
  });

  it('handles string values', () => {
    const items = [{ price: '10', quantity: '3' }];
    expect(calculateTotal(items)).toBe(30);
  });
});</code></pre><br>These tests cover: ✅ normal operation, ✅ empty input, ✅ null/undefined, ✅ missing fields, and ✅ type coercion.

